data.content:
Three breaking changes affect your code:

---

## 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now accepts a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your expression-tree construction **won't compile** because the overload now takes `Func<…>` instead of `Expression<Func<…>>`. Replace with simple imperative code:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` gymnastics needed.

---

## 2. Complex type column names — two related changes

**a) Same-named properties across complex types are now uniquified** (appended number to avoid silent column sharing):

Your `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared a column. Now they get distinct names. To preserve the old behavior, pin column names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path** in column names. Your `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to `BillingAddress_City`; it now becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **Tip:** If you have existing migrations, generate a new migration after upgrading — the renamed columns will show up as renames. Pin with `HasColumnName` to suppress them.

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All diagnostic methods (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) gained a `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted-SQL logging. Update your signature:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

The new parameter provides SQL with inlined constants redacted (unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging` is on), while `command.CommandText` still contains the real executed SQL.
